  <a href="#Xbeverton1957dynamics">1957</a>); <a href="#Xsmith1973stability">Maynard Smith and Slatkin</a> (<a href="#Xsmith1973stability">1973</a>); <a href="#Xgetz1989ecogenetic">Getz and Kaitala</a> (
  <a href="#Xgetz1989ecogenetic">1989</a>); <a href="#Xgetz1996hypothesis">Getz</a> (<a href="#Xgetz1996hypothesis">1996</a>). This homology explains in particular the analogy between the qualitative results of our two-species
  first order model with the results of a Lotka-Volterra two-species system.
</p>
<p class="indent">
  In this work, we focused on the structural stability of our modeling, by introducing a friction term. A strong friction makes the system tend towards a first order behavior: inertia loses its dynamical importance. In the general models
  presented above, friction affects relaxation but not the equilibrium stability. This will not be the case in the next section anymore.
</p>
<p class="indent">
  Our model shows how the same equational form can be interpreted at the first or the second order (keeping in mind that the dimension and the meaning of the parameters change according to the order). At the first order, the system
